England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","St. Quinton Castle, Wales":"Castle, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Quintin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Yves, Andre, Dominique, Gilles, Lucien, Michel, Oliva, Roch.","Breton: from the personal name <i>Quintin</i>, which is of the same Latin origin as 2 below, but also considered a derivative of Old Breton <i>kint</i> ‘first’.","French; Spanish (<b>Quintín</b>): from the personal name <i>Quintin</i> (Spanish <i>Quintín</i>), from Latin <i>Quintinus</i>, a Christian saint's name (see   Quentin  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Quinton","meanings":["English: from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Quentin</i>, <i>Quintin</i> (Latin <i>Quintinus</i>, a suffixed form of <i>quintus</i> ‘fifth’), popular in France from the cult of Saint Quentin of Amiens, and brought to England by the Normans. The surname was altered to <i>Quinton</i> by association with the placenames in 2 below.","English: habitational name from from any of three places called Quinton (Gloucestershire, Northamptonshire, Worcestershire) or from Quainton (Buckinghamshire). The placenames probably derive from Old English <i>cwēn</i> ‘queen’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, or perhaps from Old English <i>cwene</i> ‘woman’ + <i>tūn</i> or an Old English personal name <i>Cwēna</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i>.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Saint-Quentin (Manche) in France or possibly from Saint-Quentin-en-Tourmont (Somme), the site of the martyrdom of Saint Quentin of Amiens, a 3rd-century Roman missionary to Gaul. It is not certain that this surname survived into the modern period."]},{"name":"Quentin","meanings":["French: from the Old French personal name <i>Quentin</i> (from Latin <i>Quintinus</i>, a suffixed form of <i>quintus</i> ‘fifth’), popular in France from the cult of Saint Quentin of Amiens, a 3rd-century Roman missionary to Gaul. Compare   Quintin  .","English: variant of   Quinton  ."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Herbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Heribert","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Herbert Quintin I was born in 1066, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Lady Agnes de Arches about 1159. He died in Castle, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1066–":"1066–Surnud","1072–Female":"1072–Surnud","1028–Female":"1028–Surnud","1098–1136":"1098–1136","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1066–Male":"1066–Surnud","1028":"1028","ABT 1098":"umbes 1098","1136":"1136","Abt 1100":"umbes 1100","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","about 1159":"umbes 1159","1098":"1098","1072":"1072","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St. Quinton Castle,, Wales":"Castle, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Skipsey, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St. Quinton Castle, Wales":"Castle, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1066–":"1066–Kuollut","1072–Female":"1072–Kuollut","1028–Female":"1028–Kuollut","1098–1136":"1098–1136","1100–Female":"1100–Kuollut","1066–Male":"1066–Kuollut","1028":"1028","ABT 1098":"noin 1098","1136":"1136","Abt 1100":"noin 1100","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","about 1159":"noin 1159","1098":"1098","1072":"1072","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","St. Quinton Castle,, Wales":"Castle, Montgomeryshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Skipsey, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","St. Quinton Castle, Wales":"Castle, Montgomeryshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1066–":"1066–Décédé","1072–Female":"1072–Décédée","1028–Female":"1028–Décédée","1098–1136":"1098–1136","1100–Female":"1100–Décédée","1066–Male":"1066–Décédé","1028":"1028","ABT 1098":"environ 1098","1136":"1136","Abt 1100":"environ 1100","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","about 1159":"environ 1159"